Putin the Culprit
Moscow—German, French, and Swedish medical experts all agree that Alexei Navalny was poisoned with Novichok nerve agent. Navalny is Russia's most prominent opponent of President Putin and the founder of the Anti-Corruption Foundation.
Fortunately, Navalny’s survival has prevented further deterioration of relations between Russia and Germany.
To clarify her "position," German Chancellor Merkel declared that Navalny is a "victim persecuted for his free speech."
In her view, this incident is very serious and can only be addressed by the Russian government.
She emphasized that the whole world needs an explanation.
Merkel called for the Russian authorities to conduct an independent and transparent investigation.
The EU and the UK also support this call.
If the investigation proves that the Russian government is behind the incident, the EU Commission will impose new sanctions.
Regardless, poisoning is prohibited under the terms of the Chemical Weapons Convention.
This is not the first time Putin's government has used the nerve agent Novichok against its own political opponents.
In 2018, Russian former double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both survived and went into hiding.
The Kremlin denied both incidents strongly.
Regarding the Navalny incident, Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov insisted there is "no evidence to blame the Russian government."
Russian Federal Security Service Director Sergei Naryshkin even said it was the behavior of Western intelligence agencies, framing the credibility of the Russian government.
Naryshkin's statement is clearly unreasonable, but he does point out a fact: the Navalny incident is more harmful than beneficial to Russia.
Poisoning a famous political opponent before the upcoming election, and using a毒剂 developed by the former Soviet Union, is hard to explain.
Especially at a time when neighboring Belarusian citizens are protesting the August elections.
Moreover, the Kremlin's initial reaction to the Navalny incident is particularly puzzling.
Shouldn't the Russian government have planned more carefully before committing the crime?
If, as Germany claims, it was indeed the Russian government, then this murder attempt was a failed operation.
Putin has always been like Darth Vader in international politics, intervening in US elections, fomenting street protests in France, luring Britain to leave the EU, and supporting Bashar al-Assad in Syria.
As a former KGB officer, he is shrewd, far-sighted, and cunning.
Why couldn't he kill Skripal and Navalny?
Why did Navalny escape to Germany and get confirmed as poisoned so quickly?
Now, Putin faces international condemnation and sanctions, with the Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline to Germany potentially canceled.
This assassination attempt clearly does not pay off.
In fact, it further stirs up public opposition to the Russian authorities.
Even if it wasn't Putin who did it, blaming Western intelligence agencies is even more over-the-top.
if such accusations hold true, German and Swedish scientists wouldn't have revealed the truth about the nerve agent Novichok.
More likely, it was a conspiracy orchestrated by Putin's political inner circle.
Perhaps Putin needed Navalny to be quiet before the election, or perhaps his anti-corruption investigations got him into trouble.
In Russia, you can find all sorts of products and services on the black market, including military-grade nerve agents.
Putin's political enforcers, though loyal, are quite stupid; they thought poisoning Navalny was a good idea, and only a few knew the truth.
Other failed poisonings have similar characteristics: the poisoning of journalists Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017, who coordinated the Hudyokov Public Investigation Committee.
The poisoning of Peter Verzilov, the publisher of the independent media outlet Mediazona, in 2018.
Mediazona is a website that reports on Russian judicial abuses.
Going further back, there was the poisoning of Alexander Litvinenko in 2006, a former FSB officer who frequently criticized Russia's security agencies.
Just like the Navalny case, these poisonings often backfire.
